#week-title("One", "The Caput Mortuum & The First Burning")

=== Core Teaching

After maceration, the liquid essence has been separated from the body of the
herb. What remains — the dead residue soaked in alcohol — is called the feces,
or in alchemical language, the *Caput Mortuum* (the dead head). Most practitioners
in other traditions discard this. The alchemist does not.

This week, pour off your Melissa macerate and seal it in a clean, dark glass
vessel. The remaining feces are to be burned to ash. This is *calcination* — the
first great operation of the alchemical art. The process begins outdoors, with
the herb's remains burning in an earthenware or porcelain dish.

=== Topics This Week

- The Caput Mortuum: why we do not discard the "dead head"
- Pouring off and sealing the macerate
- Initial burning protocol: safety and wind considerations

#inner-work[
  *Desoille's Descending Movement*

  Calcination in the inner work corresponds to what Robert Desoille calls the
  *Descending movement* — the deliberate turning of inner attention downward into
  the shadow regions of the psyche.

  This is not an exercise in wallowing in darkness, but a diagnostic survey: a
  clear-eyed inventory of what has been carried too long, what erroneous beliefs
  have been calcified into habit, and what "primitive tendencies" have been
  repressed.

  *The Practice:*
  Sit in your meditation posture. After the inner flame, allow an image of a
  dark, descending place to form — a cave, a stairway, or a forest at night. Do
  not force the image; allow it to arise. Record your initial impressions.
]

